e popular discourse around new media. Drawing on extensive research into hacking culture, fan communities, and Web 2.0 applications, Schäfer offers a critical approach to the hype around user participation and exposes the blurred boundaries between industry-driven culture and the domain of the user.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aComputersxSocial aspects. 0aInternetxSocial aspects. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aSchäfer, Mirko Tobias, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060651508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066278840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048513154zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048513154423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048513154.jpg  a978-3-11-060651-5  AUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066278-8  Amsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2002d2015  a978-3-11-070067-1  AUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK